My dark night in the Land of the Rising Sun
It’s every expat’s nightmare – falling seriously ill in a foreign land. Yet, as Jeremy Hill explains, his spell in a Tokyo hospital made him glad to live there Jeremy Hill with his children Justin and Jemma, enjoying the cherry blossom in a Tokyo park shortly after his discharge from hospital Photo: Jeremy Hill	9:55AM BST 04 Oct 2013
Comments
"Your face looks funny. I’m going to call an ambulance," said my partner, Yukiko, as I lay on the sofa watching the latest Batman DVD one cold winter’s night in Tokyo, feeling very sorry for myself with a heavy head cold. "That’s strange,” I thought, "my face has been funny for the last 50 years and no one’s ever sent me to hospital before." But then again, the Japanese tend to go to hospital for minor ailments just as we would visit our GP in England. Perhaps this was just another of those cultural quirks that had been enriching my life in Japan for the previous three years. Soon afterwards, however, I was in an ambulance. Although my Japanese is not fluent I could understand them calling ahead to find an emergency bed for the foreigner with the funny face. Then it all got very fuzzy. When I came to, I was surrounded by nurses who were asking me to smile at them and squeeze their hands. "So there is a heaven," I thought. Then the doctors asked me to raise my arms in a banzai-type salute. My right arm made it but there was no movement in my left. It gradually dawned on me that I was in intensive care having suffered a serious stroke, and it was only the quick thinking and action by Yukiko and the medical experts that meant I regained consciousness as quickly as I did. I spent a month in the Toho University Hospital in central Tokyo, going through all manner of clinical tests and scans. The nurses struggling to lift me had also recommended a strict diet to reduce my weight to the Asian BMI standards. They didn’t understand that I wasn’t too heavy, I was just too short. They were also keen to add to their very limited English medical vocabulary for bodily functions, so I quickly taught them the words "pee" and "pooh" – possibly laying the foundations for my current post-retirement job as an English language coach. Related Articles
