Expat guide to Japan: health care
11 May 2011
As a foreigner, I was given the option of having bread with my nutritious Japanese meals of grilled fish, miso soup and broccoli; with hindsight, after a month of receiving a slab of white toast and catering-pack marmalade with every meal, I wished I’d chosen the bowl of rice. But being right-handed, using chopsticks to eat was a definite advantage while I still couldn’t move my left arm. Within a week I started daily physiotherapy or "rehabili". My rehab doctor was, like me, a music fan, so while he took me through my exercises we’d talk about our shared interest in British classic rock. I began to look forward to these sessions – instead of "one, two, three, and four" as I lurched along the parallel bars, it would be "Bowie, Clapton, Queen and Floyd". After a month I could walk with a stick and move small objects with my left hand, and was transferred to the Hatsudai rehabilitation hospital. There I did three to four hours’ intensive physical and occupational therapy every day with some "concentration" or "attentiveness" exercises and tests. It was a combination of Playschool and bootcamp. The physical trainers tried to give me instructions in simple English (stretch, relax, push, pull, up, down) but the occupational therapy was more of a challenge. Word association and mental maths may be standard brain training for stroke recovery, but in Japanese it really got my damaged grey cells active again. A key feature of the rehabilitation was to return to a normal life-style, so patients had their own rooms, dressed in everyday clothes and ate meals in a dining room with fellow patients. Conversations with my table mates, Nagai-san and Honda-san, again stretched my listening skills as they had both suffered speech impairment with their strokes, but with pictures and a lot of laughs we got on very well and still keep in touch. In the clear spring air from the dining room, we had a fantastic view of a snow-capped Mount Fuji rising from the distant horizon over the urban landscape – a real inspiration to reach for the heights. We were also encouraged to set some personal goals to facilitate recovery. Pre-stroke, a friend of mine had bought me a ticket to see Eric Clapton play at the Budokan arena and I was determined to go – so after protracted negotiations with the head of the hospital I got permission, with Yukiko pushing me in a wheelchair, though only after she'd had a few driving lessons. At the end of the concert, as Eric left the stage, I managed to raise my left arm completely – a slow-arm greeting for "Slowhand”. My next goal was to be able to run again. I got fitter with a lot of balance and co-ordination exercises, and was pleased to have my daily walk outside the hospital building increase from 10 to 30 minutes. I finally persuaded the staff who accompanied me to allow me to break into a jog on occasions – a wonderful sense of freedom. In the end they used to draw lots as to who didn’t have to go jogging with the crazy gaijin (foreigner). With regular assessments I looked forward to being discharged to achieve my third objective – to go to Narita airport unaided to meet my teenaged son and daughter who, not having given up faith in their old man, were going ahead with their planned Easter holiday visit to Japan. The fact that I made it was a physical and emotional breakthrough, even though navigating the crowds in the local park for a picnic lunch under the cherry blossoms remained a challenge. But it was a chance to reflect on how lucky I had been to have received such excellent medical care at the hands of the Japanese health service, following that dark night four months previously. Jeremy Hill, 56, who is originally from Northampton, England, spent 35 years working as a British diplomat. He was posted to Japan twice in his career and stayed there after he retired. He now works as an English language teacher and corporate trainer. Expat Life
