Iraq
Iraq withdrawal: background to the war The Iraq war sharply divided opinion over whether ousting Saddam Hussein's brutal regime justified the enormous human and financial cost. Link to this video
10:00AM BST 30 Apr 2009
British forces invaded Iraq in March 2003 under a cloud of political controversy about the legality of military action and amid intense public opposition to the conflict.After an initial honeymoon period when many Iraqis welcomed them as liberators, British troops found themselves mired in a vicious Iran-backed Shiite insurgency.But after more than six years in the country - longer than the duration of the Second World War - they are now returning home leaving southern Iraq a more peaceful and optimistic place.The security situation in the city of Basra is greatly improved, although rebuilding shattered homes and ensuring everyone has access to clean water and electricity will take much longer.Historians will debate the political and military rights and wrongs of the Iraq war for many decades to come.
