Nick Clegg, the Libderal Democrat leader, has suggested it was Britain's "most disastrous foreign policy blunder" since the Suez crisis more than 50 years ago.The Falklands War had a significantly higher UK death toll, but the drawn-out battle in Iraq against an often invisible enemy put a huge strain on the troops.A total of 179 British personnel - 178 servicemen and women and one civilian Ministry of Defence worker - died serving in the Iraq campaign.Among the worst losses of life were the murder of six Red Caps by an angry mob in June 2003 and the deaths of 10 personnel when an RAF Hercules was shot down near Baghdad in January 2005.Both incidents led to embarrassing questions for ministers about how well British servicemen and women were equipped before being sent off to war.There was further controversy about a number of prisoner abuse scandals involving British troops - isolated incidents, as the military stressed, but very damaging.A public inquiry later this year will examine the case of Baha Mousa, a 26-year-old hotel receptionist in Basra who was beaten to death in September 2003 while in the custody of British soldiers.But it should not be forgotten that Britain's forces also demonstrated great stoicism and heroism while serving in Iraq.This was exemplified by Private Johnson Beharry, who became the first person to be awarded the Victoria Cross in more than two decades for his extraordinary bravery during two fierce ambushes in the southern city of Al Amarah in May and June 2004.British generals acknowledge the campaign has been extremely difficult but say they are leaving Basra a much better place.Major General Andy Salmon, until last month the UK's top commander in Iraq, said in a recent interview: "I can put my hand on my heart and say we've finished this right."Nonetheless the UK - which also occupied Iraq during both World Wars - leaves behind a mixed legacy.People in Basra are grateful to be free from the tyranny of Saddam Hussein's rule but some blame the foreign troops for the troubles that have beset their country since 2003.A recent survey found that only 36 per cent of Iraqis believed the presence of British forces had been positive and 42% felt it was negative.Now the UK pullout brings Iraq a step closer to taking control of its own destiny. Iraq
